mer Olympics \u2013 Finn]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1960 Summer Olympics \u2013 Finn]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1968 Summer Olympics \u2013 Star]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1972 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Tornado]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Tornado]]\n[[Category:World champions in sailing for Denmark]]\n[[Category:Finn class world champions]]\n[[Category:Flying Dutchman class world champions]]\n[[Category:Snipe class world champions]]\n[[Category:Star class world champions]]\n[[Category:European Champions Soling]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:World Champions Soling]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox sailor\n| name           = Paul Elvstr\u00f8m\n| image          = Paul Elvstr\u00f8m c1972.jpg\n| caption        = Elvstr\u00f8m {{circa}} 1972\n| fullname       = Paul Bert Elvstr\u00f8m\n| nicknames      = \n| nationality    = Danish\n| classes        = [[5.5 Metre (keelboat)|5.5 Metre]], [[505 (dinghy)|505]], [[Finn (dinghy)|Finn]], [[Firefly (dinghy)|Firefly]], [[Flying Dutchman (dinghy)|Flying Dutchman]], [[Snipe (dinghy)|Snipe]], [[Soling]], [[Star (sailboat)|Star]], [[Tornado (sailboat)|Tornado]]\n| club           = Hellerup Sejlklub, Gentofte\n| collegeteam    = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1928|2|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Hellerup]], [[Denmark]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Eight Bells: Paul Elvstrom|url=http://www.sailingscuttlebutt.com/2016/12/07/eight-bells-paul-elvstrom/|accessdate=8 December 2016}}</ref>\n| death_date     = {{death date and age |2016|12|07 |1928|02|25 |df=yes}}\n| death_place    = [[Hellerup]], [[Denmark]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Han vandt fire OL-guldmedaljer: Sejleren Paul Elvstr\u00f8m er d\u00f8d |url=http://www.b.dk/sport/han-vandt-fire-ol-guldmedaljer-sejleren-paul-elvstroem-er-doed|publisher=[[Berlingske Tidende]]|language=Danish|accessdate=8 December 2016}}</ref>\n| height         = {{height|m=1.82}}\n| weight         = {{convert|85|kg|lb|abbr=on}}\n| retired        = 1988\n| show-medals    = no\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalCountry | {{DEN}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[International athletics championships and games|International athletics competitions]] }}\n{{MedalCount\n| [[Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]] | 4 | 0 | 0\n| [[World championships in sailing|World championships]] | 11 | 2 | 2\n| total = yes\n}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Olympic Games]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[1948 Summer Olympics|1948 London]] | [[Sailing at the 1948 Summer Olympics \u2013 Firefly|Firefly class]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[1952 Summer Olympics|1952 Helsinki]] | [[Sailing at the 1952 Summer Olympics \u2013 Finn|Finn class]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[1956 Summer Olympics|1956 Melbourne]] | [[Sailing at the 1956 Summer Olympics \u2013 Finn|Finn class]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[1960 Summer Olympics|1960 Rome]] | [[Sailing at the 1960 Summer Olympics \u2013 Finn|Finn class]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World championships in sailing|World championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold | 1957 La Baule | 505 class }}\n{{MedalGold | 1958 La Baule | 505 class }}\n{{MedalGold | 1958 Zeebrugge | Finn class }}\n{{MedalGold | 1959 Copenhagen | Finn class }}\n{{MedalGold | 1959 Porto Alegre | Snipe class }}\n{{MedalGold | 1962 St.&nbsp;Petersburg | Flying Dutchman class }}\n{{MedalGold | 1966 Copenhagen | 5.5 metres class }}\n{{MedalGold | 1966 Kiel | Star class }}\n{{MedalGold | 1967 Copenhagen | Star class }}\n{{MedalGold | 1969 Copenhagen | Soling class }}\n{{MedalGold | 1974 Sydney | Soling class }}\n{{MedalSilver | 1956 Burnham | Finn class }}\n{{MedalSilver | 1969 San Diego | Star class }}\n{{MedalBronze | 1971 New York | Soling class }}\n{{MedalBronze | 1985 Travem\u00fcnde | Tornado class }}\n}}\n[[File:Paul Elvstr\u00f8m 1960.jpg|thumb|235px|Elvstr\u00f8m at the 1960 Olympics]]\n[[File:Paul Elvstr\u00f8m 1960b.jpg|thumb|235px|Elvstr\u00f8m at the 1960 Olympics]]\n\n'''Paul Bert Elvstr\u00f8m''' (25 February 1928 &ndash; 7 December 2016) was a Danish [[yachtsman]]. He won four Olympic gold medals and thirteen world titles<ref>https://elvstromsails.com/info/paul-elvstrom</ref> in a range of classes including [[Snipe (dinghy)|Snipe]], [[Soling]], [[Star (sailboat)|Star]], [[Flying Dutchman (dinghy)|Flying Dutchman]] and [[Finn (dinghy)|Finn]].\n\n==Biography==\nElvstr\u00f8m competed in eight [[Olympic Games]] from 1948 to 1988, being one of only six persons ever (the others are sailor [[Ben Ainslie]], swimmer [[Michael Phelps]], wrestler [[Kaori Icho]], and athletes [[Carl Lewis]] in the long jump and [[Al Oerter]] in the discus) to win four consecutive individual gold medals (1948\u201360), first time in a Firefly, subsequently in Finns.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.olympic.org/uk/athletes/profiles/bio_uk.asp?par_i_id=37250 |title = International Olympic Committee \u2013 Athletes |accessdate = 2008-08-13}}</ref> In his last two Olympic games he sailed the [[Tornado (sailboat)|Tornado]] Catamaran class, which, in those days, was normally sailed by two young men, with his daughter [[Trine Elvstr\u00f8m]] as forward hand.<ref name=sr>{{cite Sports-Reference|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/el/paul-elvstrom-1.html|title=Paul Elvstr\u00f8m|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925020316/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/el/paul-elvstrom-1.html|archivedate=25 September 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe is one of only four athletes who have competed in the Olympics over a span of 40 years, along with fencer [[Ivan Joseph Martin Osiier]], sailor [[Magnus Konow]], and sailor [[Durward Knowles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=biWfNzQiR8EC&pg=PA447&dq=Ivan+Joseph+Martin+Osiier&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjAjobhl6TbAhUIYK0KHYfdDAUQ6AEIPjAG#v=onepage&q=Ivan+Joseph+Martin+Osiier&f=false|title=Guinness World Records 2012|first=Craig|last=Glenday|date=29 November 2018|publisher=Bantam Books|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nElvstr\u00f8m was also noted as a developer of sails and sailing equipment. One of his most successful innovations was a new type of self-bailer. The design is still in production under the Andersen brand and has been widely copied. The new features were a wedge shaped venturi that closes automatically if the boat grounds or hits an obstruction, and a flap that acts as a non return valve to minimise water coming in if the boat is stationary or moving too slowly for the device to work. Previous automatic bailers would be damaged or destroyed if they met an obstruction, and would let considerable amounts of water in if the boat was moving too slowly.\n\nElvstr\u00f8m was a very early innovator in training techniques. For example, he used the technique of 'sitting out' or [[hiking (sailing)|hiking]] using [[toe-straps]] to a greater degree than previously, getting all his body weight from the knees upwards outside the boat, thus providing extra leverage to enable the boat to remain level in stronger winds and hence go faster than his competitors. This technique required great strength and fitness, so Elvstr\u00f8m built a training bench with toe-straps in his garage to replicate the sitting-out position in his dinghy. He then proceeded to spend many training hours on dry land sitting out on the bench at home.\n\nHe also popularised the [[kicking strap]], or boom vang (US). This may take the form of a [[block and tackle]] linking a low point on the [[Mast (sailing)|mast]] (or an equivalent point on the hull) and the [[Boom (sailing)|boom]] close to the mast, which allows the boom to be let out when [[reaching (sailing)|reaching]] or [[running (sailing)|running]] without lifting. This controls the twist of the [[mainsail]] from its foot to its head, increasing the sail's power and the boat's speed and controlability. Elvstr\u00f8m did not advertise his new invention, leaving his competitors mystified at his superior boat-speed. Investigation of his dinghy revealed nothing as he used to remove the kicking strap before coming ashore.\n\nHe established a manufacturing company whose products included masts, booms, and sails. He has also been instrumental in developing several international yacht racing rules.\n\nAmong the innovative concepts he brought to sailboat racing was the concept of gates instead of a single windward or leeward mark in large regattas. The leeward gate on a windward-leeward course is commonly used. The windward gate is less often used due to the difficulties in managing right-of-way around the right gate, the subtleties of which are understood mostly by match racers.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.sailingscuttlebutt.com/archived_Detail.asp?key=3866 |title = Scuttlebutt: Archived Newsletters |accessdate = 2008-08-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Elvstr\u00f8m was chosen as \"Danish Sportsman of the Century.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Albrechtsen|first1=Karin|last2=Leksikon|first2=Gyldendal|title=Paul Elvstr\u00f8m |url=http://denmark.dk/en/meet-the-danes/great-danes/athletes/paul-elvstroem|website=Denmark.dk |accessdate=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Elvstr\u00f8m was among the first six inductees into the [[ISAF Sailing Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.sailing.org/halloffame/21227.php |title = ISAF Hall of Fame : Paul Elvstr\u00f6m |accessdate = 2008-08-13 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080917154021/http://www.sailing.org/halloffame/21227.php |archivedate = 17 September 2008 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> He died on 7 December 2016 at the age of 88,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andersen|first1=Jens|title=Paul Elvstr\u00f8m er d\u00f8d|url=http://www.dr.dk/sporten/oevrig/paul-elvstroem-er-doed|website=dr.dk|publisher=[[DR (broadcaster)|DR]]|language=Danish|accessdate=7 December 2016}}</ref> after battling [[Alzheimers]] for a few years.\n\n==Achievements==\nElvstr\u00f8m won medals at the world championships: [[Finn (dinghy)|Finn]], [[505 (dinghy)|505]], [[Snipe (dinghy)|Snipe]], [[Flying Dutchman (dinghy)|Flying Dutchman]], [[5.5 Metre (keelboat)|5.5 Metre]], [[Star (sailboat)|Star]], [[Soling]] [[Tornado (sailboat)|Tornado]] and [[Half Ton Cup|Half Ton]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=70% style=\"font-size:90%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year !! Competition !! Venue !! Position !! Event !! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=1 | 1956\n| rowspan=1 align=left | [[Finn World Championships]]\n| rowspan=1 align=left | {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Burnham-on-Crouch]]\n| style=\"background:silver;\" | 2nd\n| Finn\n| <ref name=THE-SPORTS>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-sports.org/sailing-elvstrom-paul-results-identity-s20-c2-b4-o42-w87888.html|title=Finn World Championships|publisher=the-sports.org|accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=1 | 1957\n| rowspan=1 align=left | [[505 World Championships]]\n| rowspan=1 align=left | {{flagicon|FRA}} [[La Baule-Escoublac]]\n| style=\"background:gold;\" | 1st\n| 505\n| <ref name=ISAF>{{cite web|url=http://www.sailing.org/biog.php?id=DENPE1|title=Paul Elvstr\u00f8m \u2013 Results|publisher=sailing.org|accessdate=21 April 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1958\n| rowspan=1 align=left | [[505 World Championships]]\n| rowspan=1 align=left | {{flagicon|FRA}} [[La Baule-Escoublac]]\n| style=\"background:gold;\" | 1st\n| 505\n| <ref name=ISAF />\n|-\n| rowspan=1 align=left | [[Finn World Championships]]\n| rowspan=1 align=left | {{flagicon|BEL}} [[Zeebrugge]]\n| style=\"background:gold;\" | 1st\n| Finn\n| <ref name=THE-SPORTS />\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1959\n| rowspan=1 align=left | [[Finn World Championships]]\n| rowspan=1 align=left | {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Copenhagen]]\n| style=\"background:gold;\" | 1st\n| Finn\n| <ref name=THE-SPORTS />\n|-\n| rowspan=1 align=left | [[Commodore Hub E. Isaacks and O'Leary Trophies|Snipe World Championship]]\n| rowspan=1 align=left | {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Porto Alegre]]\n| style=\"background:gold;\" | 1st\n| Snipe\n| <ref name=ISAF />\n|-\n| rowspan=1 | 1962\n| rowspan=1 align=left | [[Flying Dutchman World Championships]]\n| rowspan=1 align=left | {{flagicon|USA}} [[St. Petersburg, Florida|St. Petersburg]]\n| style=\"background:gold;\" | 1st\n| Flying Dutchman\n| <ref name=ISAF />\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1966\n| rowspan=1 align=left | [[5.5 Metre World Championships]]\n| rowspan=1 align=left | {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Copenhagen]]\n| style=\"background:gold;\" | 1st\n| 5.5 metres\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=1 align=left | [[Star World Championships]]\n| rowspan=1 align=left | {{flagicon|GER}} [[Kiel]]\n| style=\"background:gold;\" | 1st\n| Star\n| <ref name=ISAF />\n|-\n| rowspan=1 | 1967\n| rowspan=1 align=left | [[Star World Championships]]\n| rowspan=1 align=left | {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Copenhagen]]\n| style=\"background:gold;\" | 1st\n| Star\n| <ref name=ISAF />\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 1969\n| rowspan=1 align=left | [[Soling World Championships]]\n| rowspan=1 align=left | {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Copenhagen]]\n| style=\"background:gold;\" | 1st\n| Soling\n| <ref name=ISAF />\n|-\n| rowspan=1 align=left | [[Star World Championships]]\n| rowspan=1 align=left | {{flagicon|USA}} [[San Diego]]\n| style=\"background:silver;\" | 2nd\n| Star\n| <ref name=ISAF />\n|-\n| rowspan=1 | 1971\n| rowspan=1 align=left | [[Soling World Championships]]\n| rowspan=1 align=left | {{flagicon|USA}} [[New York City|New York]]\n| style=\"background:#cc9966;\" | 3rd\n| Soling\n|\n|-\n| 1972\n| rowspan=1 align=left | [[Half Ton Cup|Half Ton Cup / World Championship]]\n| rowspan=1 align=left | {{flagicon|SWE}} [[Mastrand]]\n| style=\"background:gold;\" | 1st\n| Half Ton\n|<ref>https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/bes-12-ton</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=1 | 1974\n| rowspan=1 align=left | [[Soling World Championships]]\n| rowspan=1 align=left | {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Sydney]]\n| style=\"background:gold;\" | 1st\n| Soling\n| <ref name=ISAF />\n|-\n| rowspan=1 | 1985\n| rowspan=1 align=left | [[Tornado World Championships]]\n| rowspan=1 align=left | {{flagicon|GER}} [[Travem\u00fcnde]]\n| style=\"background:#cc9966;\" | 3rd\n| Tornado\n| <ref name=ISAF />\n|}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Elvstrom, Paul. ''Expert Dinghy and Keelboat Racing'', 1967, Times Books, {{ISBN|0-8129-0054-5}}\n* Elvstrom, Paul. ''Elvstr\u00f6m Speaks on Yacht Racing'', 1970, One-Design & Offshore Yachtsman Magazine, {{ISBN|0-8129-0134-7}}\n* Elvstrom, Paul. ''Elvstr\u00f6m Speaks -- to His Sailing Friends on His Life and Racing Career'', 1970, Nautical Publishing Company, {{ISBN|0-245-59851-0}}\n* ''Paul Elvstr\u00f6m Explains the Yacht Racing Rules'', First edition 1969, title updated to ''Paul Elvstrom Explains the Racing Rules of Sailing: 2005\u20132008 Rules.'' Updated four-yearly in accordance with racing rules revisions, various authors and publishers. {{ISBN|0-07-145626-0}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Elvstr\u00f8m 717]]\n* [[List of athletes with the most appearances at Olympic Games]]\n* [[List of multiple Olympic gold medalists in one event]]\n* [[World championships in sailing#Multiple World champions|Multiple World Champions in Saling]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n* {{World Sailing|115872|DENPE1|Paul Bert Elvstr\u00f6m}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.sail-world.com/news/193648/Paul-Elvstr%C3%B6m-Sailings-Greatest |title=Paul Elvstr\u00f6m, Sailing's Greatest |website=Sail-World.com |date=13 December 2016}}\n* {{IOC profile|paul-elvstrom|Paul Elvstr\u00f8m}}\n* {{Olympic Channel|paul-elvstrom|Paul Elvstrom}}\n\n{{Footer Olympic Champions Finn}}\n{{Footer Olympic Champions Firefly}}\n{{Footer World Champions 5.5 Metre}}\n{{Footer World Champions 505}}\n{{Footer World Champions Finn}}\n{{Footer World Champions Flying Dutchman}}\n{{Footer World Champions Open Snipe}}\n{{Footer World Champions Soling}}\n{{Footer European Champions Soling}}\n{{Footer Danish Championship Winners in Soling}}\n{{Star World Champions}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elvstrom, Paul Bert}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:Marine engineers]]\n[[Category:Sailmakers]]\n