ichigan)|Trinity Catholic High School]] || [[Harper Woods, Michigan|Harper Woods]], [[Wayne County, Michigan|Wayne County]] || 163 || D || Lancers || Red and Blue (color)|{{color box|red}}{{color box|blue}} <small>Red & Blue</small>  || Coed || 2002-2005\n|-\n| [[Visitation High School (Detroit)|Visitation High School]] || [[Detroit]], [[Wayne County, Michigan|Wayne County]] ||  || B-C || Eagles || Blue and Gold (color)|{{color box|blue}}{{color box|gold}} <small>Blue & Gold</small>  || Coed || 1956-1967\n\n|}\n\n{{Columns-end}}\nFootnotes:\n\n'''[[Monroe County, Michigan|Monroe County]]'''\n\nCatholic Central High School, Monroe (opened in 1944), and St. Mary Academy, Monroe (opened in 1846), became [[St. Mary Catholic Central High School]] in 1986 when the two schools merged.\n\n'''[[Washtenaw County, Michigan|Washtenaw County]]'''\n\nAnn Arbor St. Thomas High School became Father Gabriel Richard High School in 1978.\n\n'''[[Wayne County, Michigan|Wayne County]]'''\n\nDetroit Cristo Rey High School occupies the former Detroit Holy Redeemer High School building.\n\nOur Lady of Mercy High School in Detroit moved to Farmington in 1965 and changed its name to Mercy High School that same year.\n\nRedford St. Agatha High School became St. Katharine Drexel High School in 2003.\n\nRedford Bishop Borgess High School closed in 2005 and became Redford Covenant High School which closed in 2009.\n\n==Accomplishments==\nSince its founding in 1926, CHSL member schools have won nearly 300 state titles (through 2015).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aodonline.org/CHSL/Hall+of+Fame+10692/Hall+of+Fame+-+CHSL+History.htm|title=Archdiocese of Detroit - The Roman Catholic Church in Detroit, MI|work=Aodonline.org|accessdate=2015-07-03}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"mhsaa.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mhsaa.com/Sports/Scores/RecordBook/CoachingRecords.aspx|title=Coaching Records|work=Mhsaa.com|accessdate=2015-07-03}}</ref>\n\nFormer [[Brother Rice High School (Michigan)|Bloomfield Hills Brother Rice]] and [[Shrine Catholic High School|Royal Oak Shrine]] head coach Al Fracassa holds the state record for all-time football coaching wins with 430 while [[Our Lady of the Lakes High School (Michigan)|Waterford Our Lady of the Lakes']] former head coach Mike Boyd is third at 361 wins (all at one school), and current [[Detroit Catholic Central]] head coach Tom Mach is fourth with 348 wins (as of 2014).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mhsaa.com/Sports/Scores/RecordBook/CoachingRecords.aspx|title=Coaching Records|work=Mhsaa.com|accessdate=2015-07-03}}</ref>\n\nCurrent [[Regina High School (Michigan)|Warren Regina]] head coach Diane Laffey is the winningest coach in MHSAA softball history with 1,118 victories<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mhsaa.com/sports/softball/recordbook/coachingrecords.aspx|title=Coaching Records|work=Mhsaa.com|accessdate=2015-07-03}}</ref> through the 2015 season.  She also is the third winningest head coach in MHSAA girls basketball with 619 wins as of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mhsaa.com/sports/girlsbasketball/recordbook/coachingrecords.aspx|title=Coaching Records|work=Mhsaa.com|accessdate=2015-07-03}}</ref>\n\nIn boys basketball, [[St. Mary's Preparatory|Orchard Lake St. Mary's]] is the state's second-winningest all-time program with 1,250 wins (as of 2009).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mhsaa.com/Sports/BoysBasketball/RecordBook/TeamRecords.aspx|title=Team Records|work=Mhsaa.com|accessdate=2015-07-03}}</ref>\n\n[[Cranbrook Schools|Bloomfield Hills Cranbrook-Kingswood]] has the most ever boys ice hockey state championships with seventeen (as of 2015),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mhsaa.com/sports/boysicehockey/yearlychampions.aspx%7ctitle=Sports%7cwork=mhsaa.com|title=MHSAA > 404|work=Mhsaa.com|accessdate=2015-07-03}}</ref> and the most boys tennis state titles with eighteen (as of 2015).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mhsaa.com/sports/boystennis/yearlychampions.aspx|title=Boys Tennis|work=Mhsaa.com|accessdate=2015-07-03}}</ref> Cranbrook-Kingswood also has sixteen girls tennis state championships, the most ever in that sport in Michigan history (as of 2015).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mhsaa.com/sports/girlstennis/teamchampions.aspx|title=Team Champions|work=Mhsaa.com|accessdate=2015-07-03}}</ref>\n\n[[Detroit St. Martin de Porres]] holds the record for the most state titles in boys track with fifteen (as of 2015).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mhsaa.com/Sports/BoysTrackField/TeamChampions.aspx|title=Team Champions|work=Mhsaa.com|accessdate=2015-07-03}}</ref>\n\n[[Bishop Foley Catholic High School|Madison Heights Bishop Foley]] holds the most girls soccer state titles in Michigan history with twelve (as of 2015).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mhsaa.com/Sports/GirlsSoccer/RecordBook.aspx|title=Record Book|work=Mhsaa.com|accessdate=2015-07-03}}</ref>\n\n[[Our Lady of the Lakes High School (Michigan)|Waterford Our Lady of the Lakes]] has the most softball state championships in Michigan history with eight (as of 2015).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mhsaa.com/sports/softball/recordbook/championshipgamerecords.aspx|title=Championship Game Records|work=Mhsaa.com|accessdate=2015-07-03}}</ref>\n\n[[Brother Rice High School (Michigan)|Bloomfield Hills Brother Rice]] has won all but one boys lacrosse state championships in Division 1 since the sport started having state championships in 2005.\n\n==Notable CHSL Alumni==\nNames of notable alumni are listed in descending order based on their respective year of high school graduation.\n\n* [[Joshua Gatt]], Professional Soccer Player,\tDetroit Catholic Central,\t2010{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n* [[Allen Robinson]], Former [[NFL]] Player,\tOrchard Lake St. Mary's,\t2010\n* [[Dion Sims]], Former [[NFL]] Player,\tOrchard Lake St. Mary's,\t2009\n* [[Ryan Riess]], 2013 [[World Series of Poker Main Event]] Champion,\tWaterford Our Lady of the Lakes,\t2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/entertainment/detroit/index.ssf/2013/11/clarkston_native_ryan_riess_wi.html|title=Clarkston native Ryan Riess wins World Series of Poker; he's second Detroit champ in five years|work=MLive.com}}</ref>\n* [[Greg Pateryn]], [[NHL]] Player,\tBloomfield Hills Brother Rice,\t2008\n* [[Mike Martin (defensive lineman)|Mike Martin]], [[NFL]] Player,\tDetroit Catholic Central,\t2008\n* [[D.J. LeMahieu]], [[MLB]] Player,\tBloomfield Hills Brother Rice,\t2007\n* [[Brad Galli]], [[WXYZ-TV]] Sports Reporter, \tBloomfield Hills Brother Rice,\t2007<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bradgalli.com/about/|title=About Brad|work=Brad Galli: WXYZ Detroit Anchor / Reporter}}</ref>\n* [[Kalin Lucas]], Former [[NBA]] Player,\tOrchard Lake St. Mary's,\t2007\n* [[T.J. Lang]] , [[NFL]] Player,\tBloomfield Hills Brother Rice,\t2005\n* [[Connor Barwin]], [[NFL]] Player,\tUniversity of Detroit Jesuit,\t2005\n* [[Morgan Trent]], Former [[NFL]] Player,\tOrchard Lake St. Mary's,\t2003\n* [[Geoff Pope (American football)|Geoff Pope]], Former [[NFL]] Player,\tUniversity of Detroit Jesuit,\t2002\n* [[Braylon Edwards]], Former [[NFL]] Player, Harper Woods Bishop Gallagher, 2001\n* [[Grant Mason]], Former [[NFL]] Player,\tOrchard Lake St. Mary's,\t2001\n* [[Matt Baker (American football)|Matt Baker]], Retired [[NFL]] Player,\tBloomfield Hills Brother Rice,\t2001\n* [[Alex Shelley]], Professional wrestler,\tDetroit Catholic Central,\t2001\n* [[Klint Kesto]], State Representative (Michigan),\tBloomfield Hills Brother Rice,\t1999\n* [[Kristen Bell]], Actress,\tRoyal Oak Shrine,\t1998<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/kristen-bell-21145185 |title=Kristen Bell Biography |publisher=Biography.com |accessdate=2015-07-09}}</ref>\n* [[Mark Campbell (tight end)|Mark Campbell]], Former [[NFL]] Player, Madison Heights Bishop Foley, 1994\n* [[Doug Brzezinski]], Former [[NFL]] Player,\tDetroit Catholic Central,\t1994\n* [[Brooke Elliott]], Actress, Riverview Gabriel Richard, 1993\n* [[Kerry Zavagnin]], Former [[MLS]] Player,\tDetroit Catholic Central,\t1992\n* [[Ron Rice (American football)|Ron Rice]], [[NFL]] Player,\tUniversity of Detroit Jesuit,\t1991\n* [[Keegan-Michael Key]], Actor and Comedian,\tRoyal Oak Shrine,\t1989\n* [[Mike Peplowski]], Former [[NBA]] Player,\tWarren De La Salle, \t1988\n* [[Scott Kowalkowski]], Former [[NFL]] Player,\tOrchard Lake St. Mary's,\t1987\n* [[Tom Lewand]], former [[Detroit Lions]]  President,\tRoyal Oak Shrine,\t1987<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shrineschools.com/for-high-school-students/winners-circle/|title=WINNERS\u2019 CIRCLE - Shrine Catholic Schools located in Royal Oak, Michigan|work=shrineschools.com}}</ref>\n* [[Craig Wolanin]], Former [[NHL]] Player,\tWarren De La Salle, \t1985\n* [[Mike Lodish]], Retired [[NFL]] Player,\tBloomfield Hills Brother Rice,\t1985\n* [[Bob Kula]], Retired [[NFL]] Player,\tBloomfield Hills Brother Rice,\t1985\n* [[B.J. Armstrong]],  Retired [[NBA]]  Player,\tBloomfield Hills Brother Rice,\t1985<ref name=\"brrice.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://brrice.edu/alumni/legacy-of-leaders/|title=Brother Rice|work=brrice.edu}}</ref>\n* [[Gus Johnson (sportscaster)|Gus Johnson]], [[Sportscaster]],\tUniversity of Detroit Jesuit,\t1985\n* [[Mark Messner]], Former [[NFL]] Player,\tDetroit Catholic Central,\t1984\n* [[Pat Shurmur]], Former [[NFL]] Head Coach, Dearborn Divine Child, 1983\n* [[Thaddeus McCotter]], Former U.S. Congressman,\tDetroit Catholic Central,\t1983\n* [[Meg Mallon]], Professional Golfer, Farmington Mercy, 1981<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mhsmi.org/advancement/golf-outing/2007|title=Meg Mallon Golf Outing - 2007|work=Mercy High School}}</ref>\n* [[Tom Jankiewicz]], [[Screenwriter]], Madison Heights Bishop Foley, 1981\n* [[Steve Phillips]], Former [[New York Mets]] General Manager,\tWarren De La Salle, \t1981<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/people/steve-phillips/|title=Steve Phillips|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=TV.com}}</ref>\n* [[Thomas Sugrue]], Historian,\tBloomfield Hills Brother Rice,\t1980\n* [[Denis O'Hare]], Actor,\tBloomfield Hills Brother Rice,\t19