was played every year from 1938 through 1967.<ref name=\"detroitathletic.com\">https://www.detroitathletic.com/blog/2012/10/01/goodfellows-game-was-tradition-at-tiger-stadium-in-detroit/</ref>  The Goodfellow Game was always played at Briggs/[[Tiger Stadium (Detroit)|Tiger Stadium]].<ref>http://www.shmsonline.org/CHSL{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} /Boys+Sports+10650/Football+10 718/Football+-+Champions.htm</ref><ref>http://michigan-football.com/f/detrtse.htm</ref><ref>http://michigan-football.com/f/pershing.htm</ref><ref>http://michigan-football.com/f/dmkenzie.htm</ref><ref>http://michigan-football.com/f/detrford.htm</ref><ref>http://michigan-football.com/f/dtcooley.htm</ref><ref>http://michigan-football.com/f/detwestn.htm</ref>\n\nThe Goodfellow Game was played in a time before Michigan had a high school state championship playoff.  As a result, the Goodfellow Game was considered one of the state's most prestigious high school football games of its time.\n\n'''Goodfellow Game facts:'''\n\n* The Detroit Parochial League won sixteen Goodfellow Games, the Detroit City League won eleven and there were three ties in the 30 Goodfellow Games played.\n*The [[Denby High School|Detroit Denby Tars]] played in the most Goodfellow Games of any school with nine.  The [[St. Mary of Redford High School|Detroit St. Mary of Redford Rustics]] played in seven Goodfellow Games, the most among Detroit Parochial League schools.\n*The [[St. Ambrose High School (Grosse Pointe, Michigan)|Grosse Pointe St. Ambrose Cavaliers]] and the [[Detroit Catholic Central High School|Detroit Catholic Central Shamrocks]] won the most Goodfellow Games with five each.  The [[Denby High School|Detroit Denby Tars]] won four Goodfellow Games, the most among Detroit City League schools.<ref>football.com/f/detrotcc.htm</ref><ref name=\"michigan\">http://michigan-</ref><ref name=\"michigan\"/><ref>football.com/f/dambrose.htm</ref><ref>http://michigan-football.com/f/detdenby.htm</ref><ref>http://michigan-football.com/f/dtstther.htm</ref><ref>http://michigan-football.com/f/rivlourd.htm</ref> \n*[[St. Ambrose High School (Grosse Pointe, Michigan)|The Grosse Pointe St. Ambrose Cavaliers]] had the most Goodfellow Game shutouts with three, while the [[Denby High School|Detroit Denby Tars]] had the most tied Goodfellow Games with two.<ref>http://michigan-football.com/f/drdchild.htm</ref><ref>http://michigan-football.com/f/hamtrmck.htm</ref><ref>http://michigan-football.com/f/dhredeem.htm</ref><ref>http://michigan-football.com/f/danthony.htm</ref><ref>http://michigan-football.com/f/rdstmary.htm</ref><ref>http://michigan-football.com/f/dtstgreg.htm</ref><ref>http://michigan-football.com/f/hwndame.htm</ref>\n*The [[University of Detroit Jesuit High School and Academy|University of Detroit High Cubs]] played in three Goodfellows Games, all representing the Detroit City League, before joining the Detroit Parochial League in 1958.<ref>http://michigan-football.com/f/udjesuit.htm</ref>\n*The Goodfellow Game regularly drew crowds of 40,000 spectators at its peak in the late 1950s and early 1960s.<ref name=\"detroitathletic.com\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! colspan=3|The Goodfellow Game\n|-\n! Year !! Winning League !! Game Results \n|-\n| 1938 || Parochial League ||Detroit Catholic Central Shamrocks 19, [[Hamtramck High School|Hamtramck Cosmos]] 13 \n|-\n|1939  || City League || Detroit Catholic Central Shamrocks 19, Hamtramck Cosmos 13 \n|-\n|1940 || Tie || University of Detroit High Cubs 20, Detroit Catholic Central Shamrocks 0\n|-\n|1941 || City League || [[Cooley High School|Detroit Cooley]] Cardinals 47, Detroit St. Theresa of Avila Pirates 6 \n|-\n|1942 ||Parochial League || Detroit Catholic Central Shamrocks 46, Hamtramck Cosmos 0 \n|-\n|1943 ||Parochial League || Detroit Catholic Central Shamrocks 8, Detroit Cooley Cardinals 0\n|-\n|1944 || City League || [[Mackenzie High School (Michigan)|Detroit Mackenzie]] Stags 3, D